<section xml:id="sec-appA-derivatives-and-linear-approximation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Derivatives and linear approximation</title>

  <subsection xml:id="appA-deriv-derivative">
    <title>Derivative</title>

    <p>
      <md>\boxed{f'(a)=\lim_{h\to0}\frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}}</md>
      when the limit exists.
    </p>

    <p>The derivative is:</p>

    <table xml:id="appA-deriv-tab-meaning">
      <title>Three meanings of the derivative.</title>
      <tabular>
        <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
          <cell>Meaning</cell>
          <cell>Description</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>slope</cell>
          <cell>slope of the tangent line</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>rate</cell>
          <cell>instantaneous rate of change</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>linear part</cell>
          <cell>best first-order approximation near <m>a</m></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appA-deriv-basic-formulas">
    <title>Basic derivative formulas</title>

    <p>
      <md>\frac{d}{dx}c=0</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>\frac{d}{dx}x^n=nx^{n-1}</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>\frac{d}{dx}e^x=e^x</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>\frac{d}{dx}\ln x=\frac1x \qquad (x\gt 0)</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>\frac{d}{dx}\sin x=\cos x</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>\frac{d}{dx}\cos x=-\sin x</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>\frac{d}{dx}\tan x=\sec^2x</md>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appA-deriv-rules">
    <title>Derivative rules</title>

    <p>
      <md>\boxed{(f+g)'=f'+g'}</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>\boxed{(cf)'=cf'}</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>\boxed{(fg)'=f'g+fg'}</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>\boxed{\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)'=\frac{f'g-fg'}{g^2}\qquad (g\ne0)}</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>\boxed{\frac{d}{dx}f(g(x))=f'(g(x))g'(x)}</md>
      This is the chain rule.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appA-deriv-linear-approximation">
    <title>Linear approximation</title>

    <p>
      If <m>f</m> is differentiable at <m>a</m>, then near <m>a</m>,
      <md>\boxed{f(x)\approx f(a)+f'(a)(x-a).}</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      The tangent line is
      <md>\boxed{L(x)=f(a)+f'(a)(x-a).}</md>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appA-deriv-differential-notation">
    <title>Differential notation</title>

    <p>
      <md>\boxed{df=f'(x)\,dx.}</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      For a small input change <m>dx</m>, the predicted output change is
      <md>df.</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Usually,
      <md>\Delta f\ne df,</md>
      but for small changes,
      <md>\Delta f\approx df.</md>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appA-deriv-second-derivative">
    <title>Second derivative</title>

    <p>
      <md>f''(x)=\frac{d}{dx}f'(x).</md>
    </p>

    <table xml:id="appA-deriv-tab-concavity">
      <title>Concavity from the second derivative.</title>
      <tabular>
        <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
          <cell>Condition</cell>
          <cell>Meaning</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>f''(x)\gt 0</m></cell>
          <cell>graph is concave up</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>f''(x)\lt 0</m></cell>
          <cell>graph is concave down</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>f''(x)=0</m></cell>
          <cell>possible inflection point</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appA-deriv-critical-points">
    <title>Critical points</title>

    <p>
      A critical point occurs where
      <md>f'(x)=0</md>
      or where <m>f'</m> does not exist.
    </p>

    <p>
      For absolute extrema on <m>[a,b]</m>, check:
      <md>\text{critical points in }(a,b), \qquad a, \qquad b.</md>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="appA-deriv-warnings">
    <title>Warnings</title>

    <p>
      Differentiability implies continuity:
      <md>\boxed{f\text{ differentiable at }a \Longrightarrow f\text{ continuous at }a.}</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      The converse is false. For example,
      <md>f(x)=|x|</md>
      is continuous at <m>0</m>, but not differentiable at <m>0</m>.
    </p>

    <p>The derivative may fail because of:</p>

    <table xml:id="appA-deriv-tab-failures">
      <title>Ways differentiability can fail.</title>
      <tabular>
        <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
          <cell>Feature</cell>
          <cell>Example</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>corner</cell>
          <cell><m>|x|</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>vertical tangent</cell>
          <cell><m>\sqrt[3]{x}</m> at <m>0</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>jump</cell>
          <cell>step function</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>oscillation</cell>
          <cell><m>x\sin(1/x)</m> near <m>0</m></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
  </subsection>
</section>
